as I said, and with precision,
and because

07:42.295 --> 07:47.767 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we feel it is very important to
make clear
both to Russia and to any other
actors that

07:47.801 --> 07:54.341 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there will be consequences for
violating norms
of international behavior, both
with respect

07:54.374 --> 07:58.912 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
to mistreatment of our
diplomatic personnel
and with respect to malicious
cyber-activity.

07:58.945 --> 08:03.850 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: You mentioned
in this long
report that there were
government organizations,

08:03.883 --> 08:07.787 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
critical infrastructure
entities, think tanks,
universities, political
organizations and

08:07.821 --> 08:10.156 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
corporations that were all
hacked.

08:10.190 --> 08:13.226 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So besides the DNC, who else was
hacked?

08:13.259 --> 08:15.528 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Was the RNC or were the
Republicans hacked
as well?

08:15.562 --> 08:19.232 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA MONACO: So, I will leave
that to the
intelligence and law enforcement
experts to

08:19.265 --> 08:23.470 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
detail in their reporting and in
their investigation,.

08:23.503 --> 08:29.142 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But what you're referencing
there is the statement
that we have made already, both
from the intelligence

08:29.175 --> 08:35.949 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
community and elsewhere, that
Russia has become
an increasingly aggressive
actor, and has

08:35.982 --> 08:43.056 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
engaged in a years-long campaign
in influence
operations and malicious
cyber-activity across

08:43.089 --> 08:46.259 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a range of public and private
sector institutions.

08:46.292 --> 08:50.630 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now, since you
have laid
out that you know who is doing
this, you know

08:50.663 --> 08:55.468 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
how they're doing this, can you
say with any
certainty that either the hacks
have stopped

08:55.502 --> 08:57.670 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and that we have defended
against them?

08:57.704 --> 09:03.376 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA MONACO: Well, what we did
over the summer
was to be very clear about what
the threat

09:03.410 --> 09:09.048 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is, and we did that by briefing
both Congress
and state and local officials,
who, of course,

09:09.082 --> 09:13.953 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
own and operate and manage the
electoral infrastructure
in this country.

09:13.987 --> 09:17.791 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we enabled them to take
steps to defend
themselves and provided them
assistance in

09:17.824 --> 09:20.527 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
shoring up their defenses.

09:20.560 --> 09:27.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, we also were very clear,
during the election
season and on Election Day, that
we were monitoring

09:27.500 --> 09:32.806 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and making sure that there had
not been an
increase in that malicious
activity, and we

09:32.839 --> 09:34.641 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
didn't see an increase.

09:34.674 --> 09:40.980 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, indeed, we are confident in
the outcome
that there wasn't a malicious
cyber-meddling,

09:41.014 --> 09:44.617 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
such that it affected the vote
count or the
voting operations.

09:44.651 --> 09:48.154 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, have all
of these think
tanks and universities and
important infrastructure

09:48.188 --> 09:52.492 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
entities, have they all been
alerted of the
types of attacks and what they
need to do?

09:52.525 --> 09:55.395 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And are we safer now that this
information
is out there?

09:55.428 --> 10:00.099 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA MONACO: I think one of the
steps we are
taking today in the responses
that we are

10:00.133 --> 10:04.938 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
issuing is, very importantly, to
expose Russian
activity.

10:04.971 --> 10:10.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so one of the elements of
the announcement
that we made today is a report
by the Department

10:10.944 --> 10:15.849 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of Homeland Security and the FBI
that provides
technical information that will
allow network

10:15.882 --> 10:20.220 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
defenders -- that's the owners
and the operators
of systems both in the public
and private

10:20.253 --> 10:23.623 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
sector -- to use that
information to defend
themselves.

10:23.656 --> 10:28.962 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So we're exposing the Russian
tactics, techniques
and procedures that they use to
infiltrate

10:28.995 --> 10:34.667 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
our systems, allowing network
defenders to
defend themselves, and,
importantly, making

10:34.701 --> 10:40.807 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it harder and more complicated
for these malicious,
bad actors to undertake these
activities.

10:40.840 --> 10:44.377 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're basically forcing them to
reengineer
their approaches.

10:44.410 --> 10:46.746 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
Lisa Monaco from
the White House, thanks so much.

10:46.779 --> 10:48.581 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
LISA MONACO: Thank you.

10:48.615 --> 10:51.684 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: This evening,
in a statement,
president-elect Trump said:
"It's time for

10:51.718 --> 10:54.687 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
our country to move on to bigger
and better
things."

10:54.721 --> 10:58.424 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But he said that, in the
interests of the
nation, he will meet with
intelligence chiefs

10:58.458 --> 11:11.538 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
next week on the Russian
hacking.

11:11.571 --> 11:16.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Russians and Turks announced
a cease-fire
deal among some of the warring
parties in

11:16.209 --> 11:17.176 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Syria.

11:17.210 --> 11:19.846 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It went into effect at midnight
in Damascus.

11:19.879 --> 11:21.881 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Margaret Warner has the story.

11:21.915 --> 11:27.387 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Confirmation
came from the
Kremlin and Russian President
Vladimir Putin:

11:27.420 --> 11:31.991 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
VLADIMIR PUTIN, Russian
President (through
translator): The agreements
reached are, of

11:32.025 --> 11:34.127 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
course, fragile and need special
attention.

11:34.160 --> 11:39.198 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But this is a notable result of
our joint
work and efforts by our partners
in the region.

11:39.232 --> 11:44.070 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: One of those
partners, Turkish
President Recep Tayyip Erdogan,
called it

11:44.103 --> 11:45.972 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
an historic chance.

11:46.005 --> 11:49.542 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RECEP TAYYIP ERDOGAN, Turkish
President (through
translator): We have an
opportunity to stop

11:49.576 --> 11:52.512 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the bloodshed in Syria with a
political solution.

11:52.545 --> 11:54.247 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We must not squander this
chance.

11:54.280 --> 11:58.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Russia has been
a critical
backer of Syrian President
Bashar al-Assad,

11:58.585 --> 12:01.120 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
while Turkey had pressed for his
ouster.

12:01.154 --> 12:07.327 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But they joined to work out this
cease-fire
and plans for future peace talks
in Kazakstan.

12:07.360 --> 12:12.065 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Russians say rebel groups
numbering more
than 60,000 fighters are taking
part.

12:12.098 --> 12:14.667 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They include the Western-backed
Free Syrian
Army.

12:14.701 --> 12:18.738 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
OSAMA ABU ZAID, Free Syrian Army
(through
translator): During the talks,
the Russian

12:18.771 --> 12:23.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
government guaranteed to us that
they will
keep the Syrian regime forces
and their allies

12:23.443 --> 12:25.211 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
under control.

12:25.244 --> 12:28.514 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Other groups
are excluded,
the Islamic State, which
controls a swathe

12:28.548 --> 12:34.854 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of Syria, the al-Qaida offshoot
Jabhat Al-Fateh
Al-Sham in the northwest, and
the Kurdish

12:34.887 --> 12:40.360 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
militia YPG battling Islamic
State's forces
in cooperation with the U.S.

12:40.393 --> 12:46.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Iran is also a major ally of the
Assad government,
and is expected to be involved
in peace talks.

12:46.499 --> 12:51.337 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Absent entirely from the
negotiations, the
United States.

12:51.371 --> 12:55.942 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Three years of talks between
Secretary of
State John Kerry and his Russian
counterpart,

12:55.975 --> 13:00.380 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Sergei Lavrov, produced a number
of cease-fires,
but they didn't hold.

13:00.413 --> 13:06.052 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Instead, 15 months ago, Russia
launched a
fierce bombing campaign to
bolster the Syrian

13:06.085 --> 13:07.587 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
regime.

13:07.620 --> 13:11.824 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Earlier this month, the rebel
stronghold in
Eastern Aleppo finally fell.

13:11.858 --> 13:16.195 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Nonetheless, the State
Department voiced support
for the truce today, saying:
":Any effort

13:16.229 --> 13:21.567 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that stops the violence, saves
lives, and
creates the conditions for
political negotiations

13:21.601 --> 13:23.302 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
would be welcome."

13:23.336 --> 13:27.707 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Russian Foreign Minister Lavrov
said today
the incoming Trump
administration would be

13:27.740 --> 13:29.876 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
welcome to join the peace talks
in Kazakstan.

13:29.909 --> 13:32.779 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: William
Brangham takes it
from here.

13:32.812 --> 13:37.483 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, will this
cease-fire
last, where so many others in
the past have

13:37.517 --> 13:39.452 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
failed?

13:39.485 --> 13:42.855 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For that, I'm joined now via
Skype from Tucson
by Andrew Tabler, who's a fellow
at the Washington

13:42.889 --> 13:47.226 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Institute for Near East Policy,
and Joshua
Landis, who directs the Center
for Middle

13:47.260 --> 13:50.096 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
East Studies at the University
of Oklahoma.

13:50.129 --> 13:51.731 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Welcome to you both.

13:51.764 --> 13:54.667 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Joshua Landis, I would like to
start with
you first.

13:54.701 --> 13:57.737 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have seen cease-fires come
and we have
seen cease-fires go.

13:57.770 --> 14:00.206 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Are you at all confident that
this one is
going to last?

14:00.239 --> 14:03.443 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOSHUA LANDIS, University of
Oklahoma: No,
I'm not confident.

14:03.476 --> 14:06.646 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This is really not about the
cease-fire holding.

14:06.679 --> 14:12.952 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's about Turkey being involved
with Russia
and Iran and essentially letting
the rebels

14:12.985 --> 14:21.094 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
know that a new page has been
turned, that
Turkey cannot keep its -- cannot
keep its

14:21.127 --> 14:25.231 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
door open to the rebels, that
it's closing
the door, and that they're going
to have to

14:25.264 --> 14:29.335 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
fend for themselves in
negotiations with the
Assad regime.

14:29.368 --> 14:31.871 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Andrew Tabler,
take that
up.

14:31.904 --> 14:33.673 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Is it your sense that this is
going to hold?

14:33.706 --> 14:38.911 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Is this, as some have posited,
that this might
be the beginning of the end of
the war in

14:38.945 --> 14:40.680 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Syria?

14:40.713 --> 14:42.448 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ANDREW TABLER, Fellow,
Washington Institute
for Near East Policy: I'm also
skeptical.

14:42.482 --> 14:44.751 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I think it's impossible to tell.

14:44.784 --> 14:49.856 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think it's very interesting
that, after
the capture of Aleppo, suddenly,
we're in

14:49.889 --> 14:51.724 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
this situation.

14:51.758 --> 14:55.461 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I agree it's important that
Turkey is involved
and on this kind of level with
the Russians

14:55.495 --> 14:57.830 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and with the U.S. out of the
room.

14:57.864 --> 14:59.632 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
That's essentially new
territory.

14:59.665 --> 15:06.105 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But what's also interesting is
by pausing
now and going into diplomacy, I
think it shows

15:06.139 --> 15:10.877 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that the Russians are setting
the table for
president-elect Trump to become
involved in

15:10.910 --> 15:12.879 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
some sort of diplomatic process.

15:12.912 --> 15:18.184 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the diplomatic process is
with Assad remaining,
but large parts of the country
being outside

15:18.217 --> 15:22.889 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of his control and potentially,
depending
on how the talks go, in the
hands of the rebels.

15:22.922 --> 15:25.992 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: There is
obviously a lot
to unpack in there.

15:26.025 --> 15:29.595 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Joshua Landis, help us
understand, for people
who haven't been following this
all along,

15:29.629 --> 15:34.767 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
let's just talk about, what's
Turkey's role,
its very complicated role in
this fight, what

15:34.801 --> 15:36.235 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
has their role been so far?

15:36.269 --> 15:38.638 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOSHUA LANDIS: Well, Turkey has
been the crossroads.

15:38.671 --> 15:42.175 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The territory has a 500-mile
border with Syria.

15:42.208 --> 15:47.413 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And across that border has
traveled almost
all the arms, the money, the
help, the fighters

15:47.446 --> 15:51.784 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that are going into Syria to
sustain this
revolt against Assad.

15:51.818 --> 15:56.556 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Russians, the Syrians, the
Iranians have
been pressuring Turkey to shut
the door on

15:56.589 --> 15:59.192 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that cross-border traffic.

15:59.225 --> 16:03.629 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Turkey is beginning to turn away
from support
for the rebels.

16:03.663 --> 16:09.969 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that is partially because of
Trump's election,
in which he said he would work
with the Russians,

16:10.002 --> 16:13.673 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and he turned his nose up at the
rebels, saying,
we don't know who they are, and
suggesting

16:13.706 --> 16:15.675 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
they're worse than Assad.

16:15.708 --> 16:17.977 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And so this is an about-face.

16:18.010 --> 16:23.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The fact that the United States
is not at
the table is very important,
because it has

16:23.316 --> 16:26.786 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
allowed these talks to go
forward without
the U.S.

16:26.819 --> 16:32.391 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in a sense, the U.S. has
signaled to
the rebels it's not got their
back, it's not

16:32.425 --> 16:36.896 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
going to continue to shuttle and
help arms
get through to the rebels.

16:36.929 --> 16:43.135 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So this is a new day for the
rebels, who have
to think hard about what their
future strategy

16:43.169 --> 16:44.470 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
is.

16:44.503 --> 16:47.340 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Andrew Tabler,
let's just
continue with that.

16:47.373 --> 16:52.044 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A certain number of rebel groups
are part
of the cease-fire agreement.

16:52.078 --> 16:54.247 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Some of them, many others are
not.

16:54.280 --> 16:57.350 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What happens to those who are
not at the peace
talks now?

16:57.383 --> 17:03.322 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANDREW TABLER: Those that are
left out of
the agreement would be subject
to Russian

17:03.356 --> 17:07.760 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
aviation strikes, as well as
regime airstrikes
and also other kinds of
operations.

17:07.793 --> 17:12.832 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, those that sign on to it
essentially go
into the cease-fire, and Turkey
guarantees

17:12.865 --> 17:17.904 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the rebel factions will not
attack from their
side, and the Russians say that
they will,

17:17.937 --> 17:21.474 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as part of the agreement, get
the regime to
stop their attacks.

17:21.507 --> 17:24.810 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Of course, these things are
harder to implement.

17:24.844 --> 17:29.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a potential way to tamp
down the violence,
at least in part of the country,
but it will

17:29.849 --> 17:36.422 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
also allow Russia, the regime
and also the
United States to more fully
target groups

17:36.455 --> 17:39.659 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
like ISIS and Jabhat Al-Fateh
Al-Sham, the
al-Qaida affiliate.

17:39.692 --> 17:43.062 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, in that way, it could focus
fire on extremist
groups.

17:43.095 --> 17:45.731 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, Joshua,
back to you.

17:45.765 --> 17:50.236 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What happens now with -- it
looks like Assad
is not going to be dislodged
from power.

17:50.269 --> 17:55.074 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He is going to have control of
some substantial
majority of his country going
forward, barring

17:55.107 --> 17:57.109 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
some unforeseen development.

17:57.143 --> 17:58.911 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What kind of a country does he
inherit?

17:58.945 --> 18:01.948 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What is his -- what's happening
with him going
